---
import TutorialLayout from '../../layouts/TutorialLayout.astro';
import CodeGroup from '../../components/CodeGroup.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<TutorialLayout title="Building Features with GSD" description="Walk through the GSD plan-execute-verify loop to build a real feature from scratch.">

	<!-- Section 1: Why You Need a Workflow -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Why You Need a Workflow</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			In <a href={`${base}tutorials/claude-code-fundamentals`} class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover transition-colors underline">Tutorial 1</a>, you built a task tracker CLI by typing prompts into Claude Code. That works great for small, self-contained features — add a command, tweak the output, done.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			But what happens when the feature is bigger? Say you want to add priorities, due dates, and filtered views to the task tracker. That's three interconnected changes to the data model, three new CLI commands, modifications to existing commands, and new display logic. If you just start prompting, you'll end up backtracking — "wait, I need to change the add command too" — or building something that doesn't quite fit together.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			This is where <strong class="text-heading">GSD</strong> comes in. GSD (Get Shit Done) is a structured workflow that sits on top of Claude Code. It breaks work into a loop:
		</p>
		<ol class="text-text mb-6 list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 pl-2">
			<li><strong class="text-heading">Plan</strong> — define what you're building, break it into slices, break slices into tasks</li>
			<li><strong class="text-heading">Execute</strong> — work through each task with Claude Code, one at a time</li>
			<li><strong class="text-heading">Verify</strong> — prove the work is done before moving on</li>
		</ol>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			It sounds like overhead. It's actually the opposite — the upfront planning prevents the rework that eats real time. In this tutorial, you'll use GSD to add priorities and due dates to the task tracker from Tutorial 1, and you'll see how the structure keeps the work clean even when the feature touches multiple parts of the code.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 2: Setting Up GSD -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Setting Up GSD</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			GSD is available as a plugin for Claude Code. If you haven't installed it yet, add it globally:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Install GSD"
			python={`# Install the GSD plugin
npm install -g gsd-pi

# Navigate to your task tracker project from Tutorial 1
cd task-tracker

# Start Claude Code with GSD
claude`}
			typescript={`# Install the GSD plugin
npm install -g gsd-pi

# Navigate to your task tracker project from Tutorial 1
cd task-tracker

# Start Claude Code with GSD
claude`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Once Claude Code launches, type <code class="text-accent">/gsd</code> to activate the GSD wizard. It will walk you through initializing GSD for your project — creating a <code class="text-accent">.gsd/</code> directory to store plans, decisions, and progress tracking.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			GSD stores everything as plain files in your project. No databases, no cloud services, no accounts. The <code class="text-accent">.gsd/</code> directory contains your project state, milestone plans, and execution history — all version-controllable and human-readable.
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">After initialization, your project looks like this:</p>
			<pre class="text-text font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed"><code>task-tracker/
├── task_tracker.py  (or .ts)
├── tasks.json
└── .gsd/
    ├── PROJECT.md       ← what the project is
    ├── REQUIREMENTS.md  ← what it needs to do
    ├── DECISIONS.md     ← choices made and why
    ├── STATE.md         ← current progress
    └── milestones/      ← planned work</code></pre>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			The key insight: GSD treats planning artifacts as first-class project state. When you plan a feature, the plan lives next to the code. When you make a decision, the rationale is captured. When you finish a task, the verification evidence is recorded. A future developer (or future you) can reconstruct exactly what happened and why.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 3: Planning the Feature -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Planning the Feature</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Let's plan the feature we're adding: <strong class="text-heading">priorities and due dates</strong> for the task tracker. Start by telling GSD what you want to build:
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-2">Your prompt:</p>
			<p class="text-text font-mono text-sm">
				I want to add priorities (high, medium, low) and due dates to the task tracker. Users should be able to set priority and due date when adding a task, see them in the list output, and filter tasks by priority or show only overdue tasks.
			</p>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			GSD breaks this into a <strong class="text-heading">milestone</strong> (the overall feature) containing <strong class="text-heading">slices</strong> (independently demoable vertical increments). Each slice produces something you can test. Here's roughly how GSD would decompose this:
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">GSD's roadmap for this feature:</p>
			<div class="space-y-3">
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">S01</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Add priority field to data model + add command</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: tasks have a priority, <code class="text-accent text-xs">add</code> accepts <code class="text-accent text-xs">--priority</code>, <code class="text-accent text-xs">list</code> shows it</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">S02</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Add due date field + overdue detection</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: tasks have optional due dates, <code class="text-accent text-xs">list</code> highlights overdue tasks</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">S03</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Add filter commands</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: users can filter by priority and list overdue tasks</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Notice the ordering. GSD puts slices in <strong class="text-heading">risk order</strong> — the riskiest or most foundational work first. S01 modifies the data model, which everything else depends on. If that design is wrong, we want to find out before building filtering on top of it.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Each slice gets further broken into <strong class="text-heading">tasks</strong> — units of work small enough to complete in a single Claude Code session. GSD tracks these at <code class="text-accent">.gsd/milestones/M001/slices/S01/S01-PLAN.md</code>. You don't need to create these files manually — GSD does it from the planning conversation.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 4: Executing: Slice by Slice -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Executing: Slice by Slice</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			With the plan in place, GSD switches to execution mode. You can run <code class="text-accent">/gsd auto</code> to let GSD work through the tasks automatically, or step through them manually. Either way, the loop is the same: pick up the next task, execute it, verify it, record the result.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Let's walk through <strong class="text-heading">Slice 1</strong> manually to see the mechanics.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3 mt-8">Task 1: Update the data model</h3>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The first task modifies the task data structure to include a priority field. GSD tells Claude Code exactly what to do — the task plan specifies the files to touch, the expected output, and the verification criteria.
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Updated data model with priority"
			python={`#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Task tracker CLI with priorities and timestamps."""

import json
import sys
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path
from typing import Literal

import click

TASKS_FILE = Path("tasks.json")

Priority = Literal["high", "medium", "low"]
VALID_PRIORITIES = ("high", "medium", "low")


def load_tasks() -> list[dict]:
    if TASKS_FILE.exists():
        return json.loads(TASKS_FILE.read_text())
    return []


def save_tasks(tasks: list[dict]) -> None:
    TASKS_FILE.write_text(json.dumps(tasks, indent=2))


def time_ago(iso_str: str) -> str:
    dt = datetime.fromisoformat(iso_str)
    delta = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - dt
    if delta.days > 0:
        return f"{delta.days}d ago"
    hours = delta.seconds // 3600
    if hours > 0:
        return f"{hours}h ago"
    minutes = delta.seconds // 60
    return f"{minutes}m ago"


def priority_marker(priority: str) -> str:
    markers = {"high": "!!!", "medium": "!!", "low": "!"}
    return markers.get(priority, "")


@click.group()
def cli():
    """A simple task tracker with priorities."""
    pass


@cli.command()
@click.argument("title")
@click.option(
    "--priority", "-p",
    type=click.Choice(VALID_PRIORITIES),
    default="medium",
    help="Task priority (high, medium, low)",
)
def add(title: str, priority: str):
    """Add a new task."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    task = {
        "id": len(tasks) + 1,
        "title": title,
        "done": False,
        "priority": priority,
        "created_at": datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(),
        "completed_at": None,
    }
    tasks.append(task)
    save_tasks(tasks)
    click.echo(f"Added task {task['id']}: {title} [{priority}]")


@cli.command(name="list")
def list_tasks():
    """List all tasks."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    if not tasks:
        click.echo("No tasks yet. Add one with: task-tracker add 'My task'")
        return
    for task in tasks:
        status = "x" if task["done"] else " "
        age = time_ago(task["created_at"])
        marker = priority_marker(task.get("priority", "medium"))
        click.echo(f"[{status}] {task['id']}: {task['title']}  {marker}  ({age})")


@cli.command()
@click.argument("task_id", type=int)
def done(task_id: int):
    """Mark a task as complete."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    for task in tasks:
        if task["id"] == task_id:
            task["done"] = True
            task["completed_at"] = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()
            save_tasks(tasks)
            click.echo(f"Completed: {task['title']}")
            return
    click.echo(f"Task {task_id} not found.", err=True)
    sys.exit(1)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    cli()`}
			typescript={`#!/usr/bin/env node
// Task tracker CLI with priorities and timestamps.

import { Command } from "commander";
import { readFileSync, writeFileSync, existsSync } from "fs";

const TASKS_FILE = "tasks.json";

type Priority = "high" | "medium" | "low";

interface Task {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  done: boolean;
  priority: Priority;
  createdAt: string;
  completedAt: string | null;
}

function loadTasks(): Task[] {
  if (existsSync(TASKS_FILE)) {
    return JSON.parse(readFileSync(TASKS_FILE, "utf-8"));
  }
  return [];
}

function saveTasks(tasks: Task[]): void {
  writeFileSync(TASKS_FILE, JSON.stringify(tasks, null, 2));
}

function timeAgo(isoStr: string): string {
  const delta = Date.now() - new Date(isoStr).getTime();
  const days = Math.floor(delta / 86_400_000);
  if (days > 0) return \`\${days}d ago\`;
  const hours = Math.floor(delta / 3_600_000);
  if (hours > 0) return \`\${hours}h ago\`;
  const minutes = Math.floor(delta / 60_000);
  return \`\${minutes}m ago\`;
}

function priorityMarker(priority: Priority): string {
  const markers = { high: "!!!", medium: "!!", low: "!" };
  return markers[priority] ?? "";
}

const program = new Command();
program.name("task-tracker").description("A simple task tracker with priorities.");

program
  .command("add <title>")
  .description("Add a new task")
  .option("-p, --priority <level>", "Task priority (high, medium, low)", "medium")
  .action((title: string, opts: { priority: string }) => {
    const priority = opts.priority as Priority;
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    const task: Task = {
      id: tasks.length + 1,
      title,
      done: false,
      priority,
      createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
      completedAt: null,
    };
    tasks.push(task);
    saveTasks(tasks);
    console.log(\`Added task \${task.id}: \${title} [\${priority}]\`);
  });

program
  .command("list")
  .description("List all tasks")
  .action(() => {
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    if (tasks.length === 0) {
      console.log("No tasks yet. Add one with: task-tracker add 'My task'");
      return;
    }
    for (const task of tasks) {
      const status = task.done ? "x" : " ";
      const age = timeAgo(task.createdAt);
      const marker = priorityMarker(task.priority);
      console.log(\`[\${status}] \${task.id}: \${task.title}  \${marker}  (\${age})\`);
    }
  });

program
  .command("done <taskId>")
  .description("Mark a task as complete")
  .action((taskId: string) => {
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    const task = tasks.find((t) => t.id === parseInt(taskId));
    if (!task) {
      console.error(\`Task \${taskId} not found.\`);
      process.exit(1);
    }
    task.done = true;
    task.completedAt = new Date().toISOString();
    saveTasks(tasks);
    console.log(\`Completed: \${task.title}\`);
  });

program.parse();`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			After Claude Code makes the changes, GSD verifies the task. It doesn't just check that the code compiles — it runs the actual commands and checks the output matches expectations:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Verification — testing the priority feature"
			python={`# Add tasks with different priorities
python task_tracker.py add "Fix login bug" --priority high
python task_tracker.py add "Update docs" --priority low
python task_tracker.py add "Review PR"

# List shows priorities
python task_tracker.py list
# [ ] 1: Learn Claude Code basics    !!   (2d ago)
# [ ] 2: Build something real        !!   (2d ago)
# [ ] 3: Fix login bug               !!!  (just now)
# [ ] 4: Update docs                 !    (just now)
# [ ] 5: Review PR                   !!   (just now)`}
			typescript={`# Add tasks with different priorities
npx tsx task_tracker.ts add "Fix login bug" --priority high
